05002nam a22005655i 9780774852166DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748521667 a10.59962/97807748521662doi  a(DE-B1597)661722  a(OCoLC)816841911  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.K55 ǂb B49 2000eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a394.2/089/974100aPotlatch at Gitsegukla :bWilliam Beynon's 1945 Field Notebooks /ced. by Margaret Seguin Anderson, Marjorie M. Halpin. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b16 b&w photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tBeynon Notebooks -- tBeynon Notebooks -- tBeynon Notebooks -- tBeynon Notebooks -- tKey Events in the Citksan Encounter with the Colonial World¹ -- tAppendices -- tNote on the Orthography Used by William Beynon in the Notebooks -- tPlace Names in the Notebooks (Including All Variant Spellings) -- tList of Names for Each Village by Clan -- tNaxnox Names and Performances -- tOther Gitksan Terms in the Texts -- tNames of the Poles -- tTypes of Contributions -- tTypes of Events -- tTypes of Songs -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWilliam Beynon was born in 1888 in Victoria to a Welsh father and a Tsimshian mother. He was an accomplished ethnographer and had a long career documenting the traditions of the Tsimshian, Nisga'a, and Gitksan. In 1945 he attended and actively participated in five days of potlatches and totem pole raisings at Gitksan village of Gitsegukla. There he compiled four notebooks containing detailed and often verbatim information about the events he witnessed. For over 50 years these notebooks have seen limited circulation among specialists, who have long recognized them as the most perceptive and complete account of potlatching ever recorded. In Potlatch at Gitsegukla the almost 200 pages of the notebooks are published for the first time. Sketches and a selection of photographs taken by Beynon are also included (augmented by photographs taken by Wilson Duff in 1952). In addition to meticulously transcribing and annotating the text of the notebooks, Margaret Anderson and Marjorie Halpin provide a comprehensive introduction that puts Beynon's account into a Gitskan cultural perspective, as well as extensive appendices listing names, places, and Gitskan terms in the notebooks. There is also an excellent timeline of key events in Gitskan history by James McDonald and Jennifer Joseph. William Beynon's notebooks are among the most significant written records of Northwest coast potlatching and are an unsurpassed resource documenting these activities among the Gitskan. This rare, first-hand, ethnographic account of a potlatch reveals the wonderful complexities of the events that took place in Gitsegukla in 1945.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Margaret Seguin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalpin, Marjorie M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJoseph, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eB